-- Monaco Mulls $54 Million Walcott Bid, Mail Says: Soccer Roundup
-- B y   D a n   B a y n e s
-- 2013-11-01T05:18:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-01/monaco-mulls-54-million-walcott-bid-mail-says-soccer-roundup.html
The following is a roundup of soccer
stories from U.K. newspapers, with clickable Internet links.  Walcott Wanted  French club Monaco is considering a 40 million-euro bid
($54.2 million) for Arsenal forward Theo Walcott in January, the
 Daily Mail reported .  Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger is unlikely to let the 24-year-old leave and Walcott is said to be happy to stay with the
Gunners, the newspaper added.  Beckham’s Boy  Manchester United has been assessing David Beckham’s son,
 Brooklyn , with a view to offering the 14-year-old a place at the
club’s academy, the  Guardian reported .  Beckham, who played almost 400 games for United, took his
son into the club’s training ground yesterday and other sessions
are planned for the academy staff to measure the teenager’s
ability, the newspaper added.  Evra Replacement?  United is set to make a bid for Saint-Etienne left-back
Faouzi Ghoulam as a potential replacement for Patrice Evra, the
 Star reported .  The 22-year-old Ghoulam, who’s played his entire career
with the French club having joined its development system at age
seven, was wanted by Liverpool, Queens Park Rangers and Torino
in the offseason, the newspaper added.  Mata to Stay  Chelsea is determined to keep Juan Mata and will resist any
offers from Paris Saint-Germain for the Spanish midfielder in
January, the  Daily Express reported .  French champion PSG made an unsuccessful 30 million-pound
($48 million) bid for Mata in the last trade period and is said
to be ready to try again, the newspaper added.  To contact the reporter on this story:
